Case Study 12 - Classifying the Higgs Boson with Neural Networks¶

Ivelin Angelov, Yao Yao, Brian Kruse

MSDS 7333 Section 402

August 6, 2018

Introduction¶

A neural network with parameter optimization is used to classify the Higgs Boson. The dataset, provided by UC Irvine's Machine Learning Repository, consists of 11,000,000 rows and 29 variables, where numerical data is generated using Monte Carlo simulations [1]. The first variable is the target label, the next 21 are kinematic properties measured by a particle detector, and the last 7 are some derivative of those kinematic properties. Previous research suggests that a ROC score of 88% is achievable [2]. After individually optimizing for neurons, hidden layers, activation, batch size, initializer, optimizer, epsilon, and dropout rate, our results show the workflow where a ROC score of 87.12% is achieved, independent of their procedure.

Methods¶

The first 10,500,000 rows are trained and validated with a 9:1 ratio and the last 500,000 rows are tested for F1, accuracy, precision, recall, and ROC score metrics. The parameters optimized are number of layers, number of neurons, activation function, batch size, kernel initializer, optimizer, learning rate, epsilon, decay rate, and dropout rate. With these optimized parameters, the final model expands the number of default epochs from 20 to 500 with early stopping to find the highest ROC score.

The steps used for this analysis are: 1) load and reduce the dataset to float16 to reduce memory consumption; 2) explore the distribution of each variable by label; 3) split the dataset into training, validation, and testing; 4) optimize parameters individually; 5) use the optimized parameters for the final model with 500 epochs and early stopping to achieve highest ROC score [3].

Note: The seed value is consistent for reproducible results during the runtime session but may still give different results when trained on CPU versus GPU [4].

Using TensorFlow backend.

The get_metrics function retrieves the current model's ROC, accuracy, precision, recall, and F1-score metrics for the test dataset.

The net function sets default parameters for a neural network if those parameters are left undefined. For the default neural network parameters, dropout is 0.1, activations is relu, initializer is uniform, optimizer is stochastic gradient descent, learning rate is 0.1, learning decay is 1e-6, momentum is 0.9, Nesterov method is applied, batch size is 5000, patience is 2, where accuracy and binary cross entropy loss functions are monitored for both training and validation datasets.

The train function sets those parameters with early stopping to find accuracy and validation accuracy of the current neural network per epoch for both training and validation datasets.

def get_metrics(y_true, y_pred, treshhold=.5):
    RocAuc=metrics.roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred)
    y_pred = (y_pred > treshhold).astype(np.int32)
    return dict(
        RocAuc="{:.4f}".format(metrics.roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred)),
        Accuracy="{:.4f}".format(metrics.accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)),
        Precision="{:.4f}".format(metrics.precision_score(y_test, y_pred)),
        Recall="{:.4f}".format(metrics.recall_score(y_test, y_pred)),
        F1="{:.4f}".format(metrics.f1_score(y_test, y_pred))
    )

def net(units,
        dropouts=.1,
        activations=None,
        kernel_initializers='uniform',
        optimizer=None
    ):

    input_dim = x.shape[1]
    assert type(units) == list and len(units) and units[-1] == 1
    units = units[:]
    if activations == None:
        activations = ['relu' for _ in units]
        activations[-1] = 'sigmoid'
    activations = activations[:]
    if type(dropouts) != list:
        dropouts = [dropouts for _ in range(len(units)-1)]
    dropouts = dropouts[:]
    if type(kernel_initializers) != list:
        kernel_initializers = [kernel_initializers for _ in units]
    kernel_initializers = kernel_initializers[:]
    assert len(units) == len(kernel_initializers) == len(activations) == len(dropouts)+1
    if optimizer is None:
        optimizer = SGD(lr=0.1, decay=1e-6, momentum=0.9, nesterov=True)
        
    model = Sequential()
    
    # first layer is special so it is out of the loop
    unit = units.pop(0)
    activation = activations.pop(0)
    try:
        dropout = dropouts.pop(0)
    except:
        dropout = 0.
    kernel_initializer = kernel_initializers.pop(0)
    
    model.add(Dense(unit, input_dim=input_dim, kernel_initializer=kernel_initializer))
    if activation:
        model.add(Activation(activation))
    if dropout:
        model.add(Dropout(dropout))
    
    for unit in units:
        activation = activations.pop(0)
        try:
            dropout = dropouts.pop(0)
        except:
            dropout = 0.
        kernel_initializer = kernel_initializers.pop(0)
        
        model.add(Dense(unit, kernel_initializer=kernel_initializer))
        if activation:
            model.add(Activation(activation))
        if dropout:
            model.add(Dropout(dropout))

    model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'], optimizer=optimizer)
    return model

default_epochs = 20

def train(model, epochs=default_epochs, batch_size=5000, checkpoint=False, patience=2):
    history = keras.callbacks.History()
    early_stop = keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(
        monitor='val_loss',
        min_delta=0,
        patience=patience,
        verbose=0,
        mode='auto')
    
    callbacks = [history, early_stop]
    
    if checkpoint:
        filepath="weights.best.hdf5"
        checkpoint = keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(
            filepath='best.h5', monitor='val_acc', verbose=1, save_best_only=True, mode='max')
      #  callbacks.append(checkpoint)
    
    model.fit(x, y, epochs=epochs, batch_size=batch_size, callbacks=callbacks, validation_split=.1)
    result = pd.DataFrame(history.history)
    del result['loss']
    del result['val_loss']
    result = result.rename(columns={
        'acc': 'Train Accuracy',
        'val_acc': 'Validation Accuracy',
        #'loss': 'Train Loss',
        #'val_loss': 'Validation Loss',
    })
    index = pd.Index(np.arange(epochs), name='Epoch')
    result.reindex(index)
    result.index += 1
    result.index.name = 'Epoch'
    result.columns.name = 'Accuracy'
    return result

Exploratory Analysis¶

Due to the size of the dataset, it is first imported as float64 and then reduced to float16 to lower memory usage to 608.4 MB. Table 1 shows how float16 still perserves data integrity compared to that of float64. Freeing up more memory saves processing speed and allocation for the rest of the neural network parameter optimization.

28 variables are plotted by label to show how some distributions are numerical categorical, some have uniform distributions, some have normal distributions, and others have skewed distributions [Figure 1 to 28]. No variable transformations are conducted prior to the neural network training and modeling. The goal is to see how neural networks perform on the original dataset to predict Higgs Boson label.

Number of layers search¶

When optimizing for layers, the default activation is relu for classification because sigmoid and tanh have vanishing gradients that do not work as well on deeper networks as relu or elu. 50 neurons are used when optimizing for layers.

In [ ]:
hparams = []
for layers in range(1,5):
    hparams.append(
        dict(units=[50]*layers+[1])
    )
print('Testing Hyperparameters:')
pprint(hparams)

trainAcc_layers = {}
valAcc_layers = {}

for hparam in hparams:
    title = "Hyper Params: %s" % str(hparam)
    print(title)
    model = net(**hparam)
    result = train(model)
    trainAcc_layers[title] = result['Train Accuracy']
    valAcc_layers[title] = result['Validation Accuracy']
    print("Test Dataset :", get_metrics(y_test, model.predict(x_test)))

Kernel Initializer Search¶

Initializers for classification perform better with normal distributions rather than uniform distributions because the separation is needed to distinguish the difference. Therefore, only initialiers with normal distributions are used as well as variance scaling and orthogonal.

Q1: What was the effect of adding more layers/neurons?¶

Adding layers improves the validation accuracy up to three hidden layers, where adding fourth layer overfits the data and has less accuracy than that of the three layers [Figure 30].

Adding neurons adds more capacity to the network and improves the validation accuracy [Figure 31]. The 10% dropout helps with overfitting. There is a big improvement between increasing from 200 neurons to 400 and a small improvement when increasing from 400 neurons to 800. Based on the results, 800 neurons is reasonable where 1000 neurons would overfit the data.

Q2: Which parameters gave you the best result and why (in your opinion) did they work¶

Our best parameters is 800 neurons per 3 hidden layers, relu activation, 1000 batch size, random normal initializer, adamax optimizer, epsilon value of 1.5e-8, and a dropout rate of 0.01 [Figure 40]. For neurons and hidden layers, they are optimized because accuracy increased yet decreased once there is overfitting with more neurons and hidden layers.

We have a binary classification problem so we need to have one neuron on the last layer with sigmoid activation and we need to have cross-entropy loss function. Sigmoid and tanh don't work as well on deeper networks as relu because of the vanishing gradients that do not do well for binary classification. Batch size is optimal at 1000 with less overfitting and high accuracy. Initializers for classification perform better with normal distributions rather than uniform distributions because the separation is needed to distinguish the difference, where normal random is the best initializer. The Adamax optimizer is tested best out of the rest of the optimizers. Epsilon of 1.5e-8 is tested to be the best numeric fuzz factor. With increasing the number of neurons in the hidden layers, we rely on a dropout of 0.01 to reduce overfitting. The default Learning Rate of 0.002 and a Decay rate of 0 are tested to be the best hyperparameters.

Q3: For #6, how did you decide that your model was 'done'¶

When searching for hyperparameters, we define reasonable hyperparameters search space around the default to tune the parameters. All the hyperparameters are chosen individually based on a grid search yet better hyperparameters could exist if all of the hyperparameters are optimized at the same time. There will always be unexplored combinations of hyperparameters and we cannot claim that we have exhausted the search space. The disadvantages of optimizing everything simultaneously are time and processing allocation.

With early stopping training by epoch, we look at the validation accuracy measured after every epoch to see if it improves, flattens, or overfits [Figure 40]. We decide that we are done training the neural network once it does not improve after the 26th epoch. Given the time and processing limits, we are satisfied with the ROC accuracy of 0.8712 given that is matches closely with the results of the previous research [2].

Conclusion¶

Searching the best combination parameter space of a neural network is an optimization problem that takes a lot of time and computer processing. There will always be unexplored combinations of hyperparameters if all of the hyperparameters are optimized at the same time and we cannot claim that we have exhausted the search space. By individually optimizing hyperparameters, we found that our best parameters is 800 neurons per 3 hidden layers, relu activation, 1000 batch size, random normal initializer, adamax optimizer, epsilon value of 1.5e-8, and a dropout rate of 0.01. Our best model with optimized parameters produced a training accuracy of 0.805, a validation accuracy of 0.782, and a test set ROC accuracy of 0.8712, where it matches closely with the results of the previous research [2].
